snippet.textDisplay:
For hackers to win, it's just a matter of looking for embedded device vulnerabilities. If any board component or add-on daughterboard has flashable firmware, the AV is pretty useless against whatever is written or addressed there. If it's not on the regular RAM or HDD, the AV software is kind of clueless.

Honestly though, I think this is more of a hardware issue at this point. And one way to address it is to make sure some things can't be updated without using a jumper to switch allow writing and having physical access. Less convenient for stuff like driver updates, but that's how it is now.
snippet.textOriginal:
For hackers to win, it's just a matter of looking for embedded device vulnerabilities. If any board component or add-on daughterboard has flashable firmware, the AV is pretty useless against whatever is written or addressed there. Honestly though, I think this is more of a hardware issue at this point. And one way to address it is to make sure some things can't be updated without using a jumper to switch allow writing and having physical access. Less convenient for stuff like driver updates, but that's how it is now.
